                        <msItem n="1" class="kon" defective="true">
                            <title type="uniform">Noregs konunga sǫgur</title>
                            <textLang mainLang="is"/>
                            <incipit>Upphaf Sveins konvngs</incipit>
                            <filiation>Incomplete copy of <title type="ms">Eirspennill</title> (<ref type="ms" target="AM02-0047-en">AM 47 fol.</ref>)</filiation>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc material="chart">
                                <support>Paper.</support>
                                <extent> 195 leaves and slips. <dimensions type="leaf" scope="all" unit="mm">
                                        <height unit="mm">323</height>
                                        <width unit="mm">215</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>
                                <foliation>Foliated 1-195 (30-39 skipped) in red ink by <name type="person" key="KriKaa001">Kålund</name>.</foliation>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc hands="1">
                            <handNote scope="sole" script="cursiva">
                                <p>Presumably a copy commisioned by <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name>. Written in a Roman
                                    cursive script.</p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>From the beginning of <title type="uniform">Magnús saga góða</title>
                                a younger hand has added variants from several codices. At the last
                                part (from <date when="1130">1130</date>) dates in <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name>'s hands are
                                found.</p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="false">
                                <p>The ms is bound in a half-binding with black leather spine and
                                    corners; the boards are covered in glossy marbled blue and
                                    brown paper from <date when="1911">1911</date>. The sewing
                                    <!-- ST: hæftning: correct translation? --> on parchment bands
                                    is probably original. Size of binding: <dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                                        <height unit="mm">327</height>
                                        <width unit="mm">220</width>
                                        <depth unit="mm">39</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <name type="person" key="KriKaa001">Kålund</name> noted the date
                                        <date when="1911-08-08">8/8-1911</date> on the upper pastedown. The cover is worn.</p>
                            </binding>
                            <binding contemporary="false" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1724">
                                <p>The binding was originally bound in parchment from an
                                    Antiphonary. This was transferred to <ref type="ms" target="#Acc-0007-b-en">Access. 7b,
                                        Hs 59</ref> f. 2 og <ref type="ms" target="#Acc-0007-b-en">Access. 7b, Hs 63</ref>,
                                    f. 1.</p>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                        <accMat>
                            <p>Ff. 123, 136-37, 149, 193 are later pasted in slips; the last one
                                contains a note by <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni
                                    Magnússon</name>. At the end of the manuscript a further four
                                loose slips are found; the content of three of them is concerning
                                this ms, the fourth contains an Icelandic satirical verse.</p>
                        </accMat>
